actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed report. This behavior is confirmed — `SKGLView` on Android uses a `GLTextureView` internally, which renders on a dedicated GL thread. The `PaintSurface` event fires from that thread, not the main thread. This differs from `SKCanvasView` (which hooks into Android's `View.OnDraw` main-thread lifecycle) and from `SKGLView` on other platforms.

Here's a workaround you can use while we investigate: cache any UI state you need on the main thread, then read the cached values in `PaintSurface`:

```csharp
private bool _isVisible;
private double _viewWidth;

// Update on main thread (e.g., in property changed handler)
void UpdateCachedState()
{
    _isVisible = myGLView.IsVisible;
    _viewWidth = myGLView.Width;
}

// Safe to read cached values on GL thread
void OnPaintSurface(object sender, SKPaintGLSurfaceEventArgs e)
{
    if (!_isVisible) return;
    // Use _viewWidth instead of myGLView.Width
}
```

Alternatively, switching to `SKCanvasView` guarantees main-thread execution, though it uses CPU rendering instead of GPU.

The fix would involve marshaling the event to the main thread in the MAUI handler, but we need to evaluate whether that would negate the performance benefit of GL-thread rendering.
